descript.abstract: Oregon Conservation Strategy Ecoregions, developed and released by ODFW, September, 2015. All ecoregions except the Nearshore ecoregion are provided from Oregon Biodiversity Information Center (ORBIC) March, 2010 ecoregion dataset, which were based on US EPA Level III Ecoregions. All Oregon Ecoregions modify the US EPA Level III Ecoregions and are clipped to jurisdictional borders of Oregon. The Nearshore ecoregion, and Coast Range/Nearshore boundary were provided from the Oregon State Boundary dataset, found on Oregon GEO Spatial Data Library (credit provided to BLM. Juristidictional boundaries were used to ensure all of Oregon is divided into appropriate ecoregions, as defined in the revised Oregon Conservation Strategy. The Coast Range/Nearshore boundary (land/water interface) represents the boundary of these ecoregions at a coarse scale, and is not intended to provide specific boundary of the Nearshore ecoregion, which includes some portions of estuaries and the entire inter-tidal, "splash" zone.
descript.purpose: Provide coarse scale boundaries for the ecoregions documented within the revised Oregon Conservation Strategy.
descript.supplinf:
Oregon Biodiversity Information Center (ORBIC), March 2010
ORBIC actions: Obtained Level III Ecoregions from US EPA (full description of the EPA layer's development is below). Clipped to Oregon State jurisdictional border. Merged "Snake River Plains" ecoregion into the "Northern Basin and Range" ecoregion. Merged minor inclusions of West Cascades ecoregion that were surrounded by East Cascades into the East Cascades ecoregion. Assigned ORBIC-convention Ecoregion names and abbreviations to the resultant 8 Ecoregions, and created a new ninth Ecoregion for the marine and estuarine waters .
Marine/Estuary Ecoregion Development: Detailed Oregon jurisdictional borders, including coastal line work and coastal and riverine islands, were obtained from Bureau of Land Management-developed shapefile, obtained from Oregon Geospatial Enterprise Office (http://gis.oregon.gov/DAS/EISPD/GEO/docs/metadata/or_state_boundary.htm).
Estuary shapefile was the Scranton/Adamus Oregon Estuary dataset, developed 2004. Estuaries were not delineated by BLM. Estuaries greater than 100 acres in size were further developed : from the Scranton shapefile, features with HGM codes of W, MSL, MSH were extracted. Because water features from the Scranton dataset often extend well upstream from estuarine/riverine partition, the Estuarine/Riverine partition from National Wetland Inventory polygons and the MSL/MSL outlines were used as a guideline for trimming the features to include only 'estuarine' water and subtidal features (in an NWI context, estuary is defined by the water's salinity). A total of 21 estuaries were then burned into the "Coastal Range" ecoregion, and given the ecoregion label of "Marine/Estuary".
The Marine/Estuary Ecoregion in the Columbia River extends to the downstream end of Puget Island, and used the NWI partition that distinguished Estuarine from Riverine. This division point also conforms to the extent of the coastal zone as defined and used by the Oregon Coastal Management Program (http://www.oregon.gov/LCD/OCMP/CstZone_Intro.shtml#Extent_of_the_Coastal_Zone). Upstream of this point, all river sections and islands in the Columbia River were dissolved into the larger adjacent ecoregion (Coastal Range, Willamette Valley, West Cascades).
For the "marine" portion of the Marine/Estuary Ecoregion, the West Coast Surficial Geological Habitat, Version 3, was obtained from http://pacoos.coas.oregonstate.edu. Geometries were clipped to an extended Oregon border. Geometries were dissolved to distinguish between Continental Shelf and Nearshore (using the Phys_Hab attribute). The resultant shapefile was then topologically reconciled with the previous linework in order to remove all overlaps and gaps. Offshore islands obtained from the Oregon Legal Border file (BLM) were given precedence over any island delineations in the Surficial Geological Habitat shapefile.
The BLM Oregon Legal Border, Scranton Estuary, and Surficial Geologic Habitat datasets distinguished several types of features, and a selection of these were retained in the creation of this dataset. The Coast Range Ecoregion has four sub-regions: Mainland, offshore Coastal Islands, Estuarine Island/Columbia River and Estuarine Island/non-Columbia River. The Marine/Estuary Ecoregion has three sub-regions: Estuary, Nearshore, and Continental Shelf.
The major estuaries of the lower Columbia River (Youngs Bay, John Day, Blind Slough) were not developed for this release; nor were smaller coastal estuaries. Instead, these estuaries are merged into the Coast Range Ecoregion (Mainland).
More background: Procedures Used (From the Level III EPA shapefile):
The ecoregion boundaries of Omernik (1987) were originally compiled at a scaleof 1:3,168,000 using a variety of scale source maps, and the ecoregion map was published at a display scale of 1:7,500,000. All level IV ecoregion delineations and most all level III revisions are digitized from the U.S.G.S. 1:250,000 base maps. For this coverage, USECO, the revised level III boundaries have been smoothed and generalized appropriately for a 1:7,500,000 display scale. 1) Prior to digitizing, each base map must be initialized to orient the map and relate it in geographic coordinates to the surface of the earth. When the registration tics are entered at the start of digitizing a transformation error of <0.003 must be achieved in order to insure a high level of registration accuracy. The person responsible for digital data entry completes a data sheet describing coverage name, date of entry, and whether a topology for the coverage is established.
1) All level IV ecoregion delineations and most all level III revisions are digitized from the U.S.G.S. 1:250,000 base maps. For this coverage, USECO, the revised level III boundaries have been smoothed and generalized appropriate for a 1:7,500,000 display scale. Prior to digitizing each base map must be initialized to orient the map and relate it in geographic coordinates to the surface of the earth. When the registration tics are entered at the start of digitizing a transformation error of <0.003 must be achieved in order to insure a high level of registration accuracy. The person responsible for digital data entry completes a data sheet describing coverage name, date of entry, and whether a topology for the coverage is established. 2) After each 1:250,000 base map has been digitized, a topology for each coverage is established. This function creates unique identities for each polygon. 3) Next each base map is tested for polygon errors through an internal editing function. Errors are corrected for unlabeled polygons, unclosed polygons, or polygons with more than one label. Topology is reestablished for each coverage and tested again until no error are indicated. 4) The digital coverage is then plotted at the same scale as the original base map. This coverage is overlaid on a light table with the original and visually inspected for replication of original lines with digitized lines. Two individuals independently inspect the coverage for accuracy.

dataqual.complete: All areas within jurisdictional boundaries of Oregon are present. The Marine/Estuarine ecoregion extends in some areas beyond Oregon's Territorial Seas.

procstep.procdesc:
Consolidated Data Basin Info: Obtained US EPA Level III Ecoregions, Feb 2009. Converted coverage to shapefile, pe-projected to Oregon Statewide Lambert. Clipped to Oregon Legal Border, using BLM high-resolution border shapefile. Merged Snake River Plains into Nrothern Basin/Range ecoregion. Merged minor inclusions of East Cascades into West Cascades. Removed extraneous EPA-supplied attributes; assigned ORNHIC-standard ecoregion names and abbreviations. Modified western and northwestern edges of Coast Range ecoregion to include high-resolution coastal border, including coastal islands and Lower Columbia River estuarine islands. Assigned all islands to the CR ecoregion, and assigned a Subregion modifier to such islands.
All islands and water features upstream from the NWI-based Estuary/Riverine cutoff in the Lower Columbia River were absorbed into the appropriate ecoregion. The Columbia River estuarine islands and the Coastal Islands were retained and assigned to the Coastal Range ecoregion. The estuarine portion (per NWI definition) of the Columbia River was assigned to the Marine-Estuarine ecoregion. Integrated the Scranton/Adamus Oregon Estuary dataset as follows: (Estuaries were not delineated in the BLM Oregon Border shapefile). Features with HGM codes of W, MSL, MSH were extracted. Because water features from the Scranton dataset often extend well upstream from estuarine/riverine partition, the Estuarine/Riverine partition from National Wetland Inventory polygons (based on the Cowardin deepwater classification system) and the MSL/MSL outlines were used as a guideline for trimming the features to include only 'estuarine' water and subtidal features (in an NWI/Cowardin context, estuary is defined by the water's salinity). Major estuaries were extracted, with "major" defined as an estuary greater than 100 acres in size. Smaller estuaries were excluded. A total of 21 major estuaries were then burned into the "Coastal Range" ecoregion, and given the ecoregion label of "Marine-Estuary" and sub-class name of "Estuary". The Surficial Geologic Habitat, Version 3, was downloaded November 2009. Features were clipped to Oregon Legal Border. Legal border extends only three miles from shore, so the border was extended westward from the Oregon Legal Border. The features were generalized on the Phys_Hab attribute, and only the "Nearshore", "Island", and "Shelf" polygons were retained. The "Island" polygons were further generalized into Nearshore polygon. The two polygons were then assigned "Nearshore" and "Continental Shelf" sub-region attribute, and a "Marine/Estuary" ecoregion attribute.
To assure continuous coverage with the other ecoregions, the Nearshore polygon was extended well eastward. Estuary sub-region (previously burned onto the Coast Range Ecoregion), together with the Coast Range ecoregion were then burned onto the Nearshore/Continental Shelf polygons.

dataExt.exDesc: Updated for the 10 year revision of the Oregon Conservation Strategy, 2015. Next planned revision is 2025.

dataIdInfo.idPurp: Provide coarse scale boundaries for the ecoregions documented within the revised Oregon Conservation Strategy.
dataIdInfo.idAbs: Oregon Conservation Strategy ecoregion boundaries are maintained by the Oregon Department of Fish and WIldlife (ODFW). All ecoregions except the Nearshore ecoregion are provided from the Oregon Biodiversity Information Center (ORBIC) March, 2010 ecoregion dataset (which is originally based on US EPA Level III Ecoregions). The Nearshore ecoregion, including the Coast Range/Nearshore boundary, were provided from the Oregon State Boundary dataset, provided via the Oregon GEO Spatial Data Library (with credit provided to BLM). Juristidictional boundaries were used to ensure all of Oregon is divided into appropriate ecoregions, as defined in the revised Oregon Conservation Strategy, and clipped at the Oregon state line. All ecoregion boundaryes are presented at a coarse scale representation , in particular the Nearshore ecoregion, which by definition includes some portions of estuaries and the entire inter-tidal, (or splash) zone.
dataIdInfo.idCredit: Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife (ODFW), Salem, OR; Oregon Biodiversity Information Center (ORBIC), Portland, OR,

Consts.useLimit: Ecoregion boundaries are presented at a coarse scale, and data set should not be used as definitive boundary lines between ecoregions.

dataLineage.statement: ORBIC's March, 2010 ecoregion dataset was downloaded from Data Basin. BLM's 2001 Oregon State Boundary dataset was downloaded from the Oregon GEO Spatial Data Library. Each dataset was converted from polygons, to polylines. All lines except the Oregon Pacific Coast shoreline and all marine boundaries were maintained from the ORBIC 2010 ecoregion dataset. The generalized Oregon Pacific Coast shoreline, and the line designated Oregon's territorial waters (~3 mile buffer of shoereline) were maintained from the state boundary line. The two datasets were then merged, and converted to polygons. Attributes were assigned to each ecoregion to designate ecoregion name, abbreviation, and code used in the 2015 Conservation Opportunity Area analysis.

dataSource.srcDesc: Oregon Ecoregions, developed and released by Oregon Biodiversity Information Center (ORBIC), March 2010. Based on US EPA Level III Ecoregions, with an additional Marine/Estuary Ecoregion that includes major estuaries and the oceanic nearshore and continental shelf.
This data layer is an element of the Oregon GIS Framework. This theme shows the jurisdictional and cartographic state perimeters for Oregon in the Oregon Lambert Projection.
